>> We are a nation
obsessed with sleep.

00:00:08.442 --> 00:00:09.743 align:middle line:90%
>> I love going to sleep.

00:00:09.743 --> 00:00:10.644 align:middle line:90%
It's great.

00:00:10.644 --> 00:00:14.147 align:middle line:84%
>> I have really vivid dreams
and usually good adventures.

00:00:14.147 --> 00:00:16.917 align:middle line:10%
And I find it really fun.

00:00:16.917 --> 00:00:19.386 align:middle line:84%
>> And many of us feel we
aren't getting enough of it.

00:00:19.386 --> 00:00:21.221 align:middle line:84%
>> I wake up exhausted
every morning.

00:00:21.221 --> 00:00:23.056 align:middle line:84%
>> It's just a
miserable experience.

00:00:23.056 --> 00:00:23.924 align:middle line:90%
And then you wake up.

00:00:23.924 --> 00:00:25.392 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHTER]

00:00:25.392 --> 00:00:26.426 align:middle line:90%
>> He won't let me do it.

00:00:26.426 --> 00:00:27.661 align:middle line:90%
>> No, I don't ever snore.

00:00:27.661 --> 00:00:28.795 align:middle line:90%
I never noticed I snore.

00:00:28.795 --> 00:00:32.366 align:middle line:84%
But I-- well, Cecily doesn't
snore more than once a week.

00:00:32.366 --> 00:00:34.368 align:middle line:10%
>> No.

00:00:34.368 --> 00:00:37.504 align:middle line:10%
>> Over a third of Australians
wish they had more sleep,

00:00:37.504 --> 00:00:39.039 align:middle line:10%
and I'm one of them.

00:00:39.039 --> 00:00:43.243 align:middle line:84%
It's 3:00 AM again,
and I'm awake.

00:00:43.243 --> 00:00:44.544 align:middle line:90%
I'm Lawrence Leung.

00:00:44.544 --> 00:00:46.480 align:middle line:90%
I'm an actor during the day.

00:00:46.480 --> 00:00:49.616 align:middle line:84%
At night, I write and
perform stand-up comedy.

00:00:49.616 --> 00:00:51.285 align:middle line:90%
I'm totally smashed.

00:00:51.285 --> 00:00:52.552 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHTER]

00:00:52.552 --> 00:00:55.589 align:middle line:84%
Then I go home to my partner
and lovely baby girl.

00:00:55.589 --> 00:00:57.357 align:middle line:90%
Nighttime means sleep.

00:00:57.357 --> 00:01:00.694 align:middle line:84%
It's a crazy, busy life,
with not much shuteye.

00:01:00.694 --> 00:01:02.996 align:middle line:84%
I really want to find out
the secrets of a good night's

00:01:02.996 --> 00:01:04.298 align:middle line:90%
sleep.

00:01:04.298 --> 00:01:06.366 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:01:07.167 --> 00:01:10.904 align:middle line:84%
So on this journey, I'll be
putting my body on the line.

00:01:10.904 --> 00:01:13.407 align:middle line:84%
And I'll find out just
how bad things can get

00:01:13.407 --> 00:01:14.875 align:middle line:90%
when you lose too much sleep.

00:01:14.875 --> 00:01:17.244 align:middle line:90%
[SNIFFS] I--

00:01:17.244 --> 00:01:19.313 align:middle line:84%
[INHALES] struggling
to stay awake.

00:01:19.313 --> 00:01:20.314 align:middle line:90%
That's what's happening.

00:01:20.314 --> 00:01:21.214 align:middle line:90%
[SIGHS]

00:01:21.214 --> 00:01:23.583 align:middle line:84%
We'll show you a test that
you can use to discover

00:01:23.583 --> 00:01:24.885 align:middle line:90%
when you're sleep deprived.

00:01:24.885 --> 00:01:26.486 align:middle line:90%
[BABY FUSSING]

00:01:26.486 --> 00:01:28.255 align:middle line:90%
>> Never been as tired as this.

00:01:28.255 --> 00:01:31.058 align:middle line:84%
>> We'll see what we can all
learn from elite athletes.

00:01:31.058 --> 00:01:33.660 align:middle line:84%
>> We're pushing our bodies
to the limit all the time.

00:01:33.660 --> 00:01:36.330 align:middle line:84%
Getting a great night's
sleep is so crucial to that.

00:01:36.330 --> 00:01:37.130 align:middle line:90%
[LOW VIBRATION]

00:01:37.130 --> 00:01:39.833 align:middle line:84%
>> And for the first time
on Australian television,

00:01:39.833 --> 00:01:42.436 align:middle line:84%
we can listen to
the sleeping brain.

00:01:42.436 --> 00:01:45.672 align:middle line:84%
>> You can hear the
neurons firing together--

00:01:45.672 --> 00:01:47.975 align:middle line:84%
typically starting from
the front of the brain

00:01:47.975 --> 00:01:49.876 align:middle line:90%
and moving towards the back.

00:01:49.876 --> 00:01:52.913 align:middle line:10%
>> A good night's sleep doesn't
seem like that much to ask,

00:01:52.913 --> 00:01:55.916 align:middle line:10%
so I'm going to meet Australia's
top sleep scientists to find

00:01:55.916 --> 00:01:59.586 align:middle line:10%
out how many of us are
getting a bad night's sleep?

00:01:59.586 --> 00:02:01.121 align:middle line:10%
What is this doing
for our health?

00:02:01.121 --> 00:02:03.190 align:middle line:84%
And how do we finally
get a good night's sleep?

00:02:03.190 --> 00:02:05.625 align:middle line:90%
[CHEERS AND APPLAUSE]

00:02:12.866 --> 00:02:15.268 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:02:16.737 --> 00:02:18.271 align:middle line:90%
>> Hey.

00:02:18.271 --> 00:02:19.439 align:middle line:90%
Do you want to hold her?

00:02:19.439 --> 00:02:21.775 align:middle line:90%
>> (SINGING) Washing love now.

00:02:21.775 --> 00:02:23.643 align:middle line:90%
Washing love hands to--

00:02:23.643 --> 00:02:25.345 align:middle line:84%
To be honest, it's
been quite a while

00:02:25.345 --> 00:02:27.180 align:middle line:84%
since I got the seven
to eight hours sleep

00:02:27.180 --> 00:02:29.249 align:middle line:90%
that scientists recommend.

00:02:29.249 --> 00:02:32.586 align:middle line:84%
So to find out if I'm missing
out on something important,

00:02:32.586 --> 00:02:34.454 align:middle line:84%
I guess the first
thing I need to know

00:02:34.454 --> 00:02:37.324 align:middle line:90%
is what exactly sleep is for.

00:02:37.324 --> 00:02:38.859 align:middle line:84%
There's no doubt
that in the morning,

00:02:38.859 --> 00:02:40.694 align:middle line:90%
my body feels refreshed.

00:02:40.694 --> 00:02:42.662 align:middle line:90%
But what's going on in my brain?

00:02:42.662 --> 00:02:43.463 align:middle line:90%
Hello.

00:02:43.463 --> 00:02:43.897 align:middle line:90%
>> Hello.

00:02:43.897 --> 00:02:44.331 align:middle line:90%
Hi.

00:02:44.331 --> 00:02:44.698 align:middle line:90%
>> Dr. Angela?

00:02:44.698 --> 00:02:45.265 align:middle line:90%
>> Welcome.

00:02:45.265 --> 00:02:45.599 align:middle line:90%
Hello.

00:02:45.599 --> 00:02:45.732 align:middle line:90%
>> Hi.

00:02:45.732 --> 00:02:46.533 align:middle line:90%
How are you?

00:02:46.533 --> 00:02:48.735 align:middle line:84%
Dr. Angela D'Rozario
explores the links

00:02:48.735 --> 00:02:50.871 align:middle line:84%
between sleep and
memory, and believes

00:02:50.871 --> 00:02:53.206 align:middle line:84%
that during sleep,
the brain chooses

00:02:53.206 --> 00:02:55.275 align:middle line:84%
which memories to strengthen
and which to lose.

00:02:55.275 --> 00:02:56.309 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah, well, thank you.

00:02:56.309 --> 00:02:56.610 align:middle line:90%
>> Oh.

00:02:56.610 --> 00:02:57.444 align:middle line:90%
There's a bed here.

00:02:57.444 --> 00:02:58.045 align:middle line:90%
Hello.

00:02:58.045 --> 00:02:58.578 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah, please.

00:02:58.578 --> 00:03:01.281 align:middle line:84%
>> So I'm going to take part in
an experiment to see if sleep

00:03:01.281 --> 00:03:03.216 align:middle line:90%
can improve my recall.

00:03:03.216 --> 00:03:04.851 align:middle line:90%
>> How is your memory?

00:03:04.851 --> 00:03:07.120 align:middle line:84%
>> Not so great I
used to be fantastic.

00:03:07.120 --> 00:03:09.856 align:middle line:84%
I used to smash remembering
names at parties.

00:03:09.856 --> 00:03:11.691 align:middle line:90%
But nowadays, I'm a bit more--

00:03:11.691 --> 00:03:12.492 align:middle line:90%
not so good.

00:03:12.492 --> 00:03:14.661 align:middle line:90%
>> Here.

00:03:14.661 --> 00:03:18.198 align:middle line:84%
>> Angela's team teach me
how to do several new tasks.

00:03:18.198 --> 00:03:20.300 align:middle line:84%
And as I learn, I
make new memories

00:03:20.300 --> 00:03:23.570 align:middle line:90%
that can be tested later.

00:03:23.570 --> 00:03:26.106 align:middle line:84%
First up, word
associations, where

00:03:26.106 --> 00:03:28.475 align:middle line:84%
I have to remember which
words appear together.

00:03:28.475 --> 00:03:29.810 align:middle line:90%
>> Some of them will make sense.

00:03:29.810 --> 00:03:30.610 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah.

00:03:30.610 --> 00:03:31.578 align:middle line:90%
>> Bread and butter.

00:03:31.578 --> 00:03:33.447 align:middle line:84%
And then others
won't be associated,

00:03:33.447 --> 00:03:34.781 align:middle line:90%
like bike and stars.

00:03:34.781 --> 00:03:35.715 align:middle line:90%
>> Yep.

00:03:35.715 --> 00:03:37.884 align:middle line:84%
>> Then I've got to
learn a new motor skill.

00:03:37.884 --> 00:03:40.821 align:middle line:84%
>> So with your left hand, I
want you to type the five-digit

00:03:40.821 --> 00:03:43.723 align:middle line:84%
sequence as quickly but
as accurately as possible.

00:03:43.723 --> 00:03:45.959 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:03:50.329 --> 00:03:53.033 align:middle line:84%
>> Straight off the training,
my memory is tested to see how

00:03:53.033 --> 00:03:53.934 align:middle line:90%
much I remember.

00:03:53.934 --> 00:03:54.801 align:middle line:90%
19?

00:03:54.801 --> 00:03:55.668 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHS] No.

00:03:55.668 --> 00:03:56.470 align:middle line:90%
Forward.

00:04:01.108 --> 00:04:03.043 align:middle line:90%
Ah.

00:04:03.043 --> 00:04:04.778 align:middle line:84%
Then it's time to
see if sleeping

00:04:04.778 --> 00:04:08.081 align:middle line:90%
can help me remember better.

00:04:08.081 --> 00:04:09.983 align:middle line:84%
While I'm asleep,
my brain activity

00:04:09.983 --> 00:04:14.988 align:middle line:84%
is going to be monitored
using a high-density EEG cap.

00:04:14.988 --> 00:04:16.755 align:middle line:90%
And I'm sleeping with this on?

00:04:16.755 --> 00:04:18.391 align:middle line:84%
>> You are going to
sleep with this on.

00:04:18.391 --> 00:04:20.694 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:04:22.095 --> 00:04:24.097 align:middle line:84%
>> This device measures
electrical activity

00:04:24.097 --> 00:04:26.933 align:middle line:84%
in my brain, and will give
Angela a detailed look

00:04:26.933 --> 00:04:28.568 align:middle line:84%
at what's happening
while I sleep.

00:04:28.568 --> 00:04:31.805 align:middle line:84%
>> We are zooming in on
particular areas of interest.

00:04:31.805 --> 00:04:34.841 align:middle line:90%
So this would be a frontal area.

00:04:34.841 --> 00:04:37.477 align:middle line:84%
>> And despite the
rather unique nightcap,

00:04:37.477 --> 00:04:40.580 align:middle line:84%
once the lights are out and
I have my cuddle pillow,

00:04:40.580 --> 00:04:42.249 align:middle line:84%
I drop off the
sleep straightaway.

00:04:42.249 --> 00:04:44.718 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:05:06.673 --> 00:05:08.041 align:middle line:90%
>> Come on, mate.

00:05:08.041 --> 00:05:09.543 align:middle line:90%
Time to get up.

00:05:09.543 --> 00:05:14.147 align:middle line:84%
>> After a blissful 90
minutes, I am cruelly awakened.

00:05:14.147 --> 00:05:15.649 align:middle line:84%
And it's time to
do the tests again.

00:05:15.649 --> 00:05:17.584 align:middle line:90%
[CLICKING]

00:05:20.520 --> 00:05:22.522 align:middle line:90%
Man, boy.

00:05:22.522 --> 00:05:26.826 align:middle line:90%
Stupid, smart.

00:05:26.826 --> 00:05:30.130 align:middle line:90%
Oh, I was close.

00:05:30.130 --> 00:05:31.665 align:middle line:90%
Shirt, innocent.

00:05:31.665 --> 00:05:32.465 align:middle line:90%
>> OK.

00:05:32.465 --> 00:05:35.368 align:middle line:84%
>> The following day, I sit
down with Angela to see what was

00:05:35.368 --> 00:05:37.771 align:middle line:84%
going on in my brain
while I was sleeping.

00:05:37.771 --> 00:05:41.241 align:middle line:84%
So after all those
tests and after my nap,

00:05:41.241 --> 00:05:42.308 align:middle line:90%
what did you find?

00:05:42.308 --> 00:05:45.645 align:middle line:84%
>> You transitioned very
quickly from wake to sleep.

00:05:45.645 --> 00:05:47.781 align:middle line:84%
So it took you a
minute and a half.

00:05:47.781 --> 00:05:51.051 align:middle line:84%
Your brain transitions through
the different stages of sleep.

00:05:51.051 --> 00:05:53.353 align:middle line:84%
And in these different
stages of sleep,

00:05:53.353 --> 00:05:56.089 align:middle line:84%
you tend to have different
depth of sleep-- different sleep

00:05:56.089 --> 00:05:57.290 align:middle line:90%
intensity.

00:05:57.290 --> 00:06:00.927 align:middle line:84%
And along with that comes some
different brainwave activity

00:06:00.927 --> 00:06:01.795 align:middle line:90%
that occurs.

00:06:01.795 --> 00:06:02.596 align:middle line:90%
>> Messy.

00:06:02.596 --> 00:06:05.332 align:middle line:90%
>> [LAUGHS] No, it looks good.

00:06:05.332 --> 00:06:06.766 align:middle line:90%
It looks normal.

00:06:06.766 --> 00:06:12.305 align:middle line:84%
These are the EEG recorded
from all of the 256 channels.

00:06:12.305 --> 00:06:14.507 align:middle line:90%
So all across the brain here.

00:06:14.507 --> 00:06:16.810 align:middle line:84%
And we can see
these oscillations--

00:06:16.810 --> 00:06:21.514 align:middle line:84%
this brain electricity
that's changing through here.

00:06:21.514 --> 00:06:25.852 align:middle line:84%
Here, where the marker
is, is a sleep spindle.

00:06:25.852 --> 00:06:27.921 align:middle line:10%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:06:28.722 --> 00:06:32.192 align:middle line:10%
>> Sleep spindles are bursts of
rapid brain activity that start

00:06:32.192 --> 00:06:34.928 align:middle line:10%
to be seen as our bodies
prepare to enter deep sleep.

00:06:37.497 --> 00:06:40.634 align:middle line:84%
Recent research shows that some
very important brain functions

00:06:40.634 --> 00:06:43.803 align:middle line:84%
are carried out during
spindle activity.

00:06:43.803 --> 00:06:45.939 align:middle line:84%
Angela is particularly
interested in their role

00:06:45.939 --> 00:06:48.341 align:middle line:90%
in memory consolidation.

00:06:48.341 --> 00:06:50.310 align:middle line:90%
So that there is a good spindle?

00:06:50.310 --> 00:06:51.111 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah.

00:06:51.111 --> 00:06:54.914 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, it's a lovely
waxing and waning spindle.

00:06:54.914 --> 00:06:59.052 align:middle line:10%
Now, spindles are important
for sleep stability.

00:06:59.052 --> 00:07:04.090 align:middle line:10%
And also, they are important for
the consolidation of memories

00:07:04.090 --> 00:07:04.891 align:middle line:10%
during sleep.

00:07:04.891 --> 00:07:06.793 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:07:06.793 --> 00:07:09.529 align:middle line:84%
>> So I experienced the
right kind of brainwaves.

00:07:09.529 --> 00:07:14.601 align:middle line:84%
But did having a 90-minute
sleep improve my memory?

00:07:14.601 --> 00:07:16.403 align:middle line:90%
I'm proud to say, yes.

00:07:16.403 --> 00:07:18.305 align:middle line:10%
And the test of my
new motor skill memory

00:07:18.305 --> 00:07:20.273 align:middle line:10%
had the greatest improvement.

00:07:20.273 --> 00:07:22.976 align:middle line:10%
>> After your nap, you
were better on the task.

00:07:22.976 --> 00:07:24.978 align:middle line:90%
So you had greater accuracy.

00:07:24.978 --> 00:07:27.247 align:middle line:84%
And also, you were
quicker at it,

00:07:27.247 --> 00:07:29.416 align:middle line:84%
so your reaction
times were faster.

00:07:29.416 --> 00:07:30.750 align:middle line:90%
[CLICKING]

00:07:31.551 --> 00:07:34.854 align:middle line:10%
>> After sleeping, I remembered
how to do the tasks better,

00:07:34.854 --> 00:07:38.692 align:middle line:10%
and my results improved
by more than 10%.

00:07:38.692 --> 00:07:41.328 align:middle line:10%
In fact, research is showing
that the links between memory

00:07:41.328 --> 00:07:44.397 align:middle line:10%
and sleep are far greater
than we ever expected.

00:07:44.397 --> 00:07:48.368 align:middle line:84%
It could even be the reason
we have sleep at all.

00:07:48.368 --> 00:07:50.303 align:middle line:90%
[SNORES]

00:07:51.271 --> 00:07:53.707 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:08:00.013 --> 00:08:01.648 align:middle line:84%
So our brains
appear to be working

00:08:01.648 --> 00:08:04.017 align:middle line:84%
a lot harder than I thought
they'd be while we're asleep.

00:08:08.355 --> 00:08:11.157 align:middle line:84%
Sleep physiologist Danny
Eckert explains just how

00:08:11.157 --> 00:08:13.159 align:middle line:90%
active the brain can be.

00:08:13.159 --> 00:08:15.562 align:middle line:84%
>> We now know that it's
a really dynamic period.

00:08:18.198 --> 00:08:21.301 align:middle line:84%
>> He's using EEG to measure
brain activity seen during

00:08:21.301 --> 00:08:23.503 align:middle line:84%
a single sleep cycle
in a volunteer.

00:08:27.240 --> 00:08:29.275 align:middle line:84%
And the brainwaves
detected by the device

00:08:29.275 --> 00:08:31.411 align:middle line:90%
are being shown on this model--

00:08:31.411 --> 00:08:33.780 align:middle line:84%
a light show courtesy
of the human brain.

00:08:38.952 --> 00:08:41.388 align:middle line:84%
>> We can see the activity
that's actually going

00:08:41.388 --> 00:08:42.188 align:middle line:90%
on in the brain.

00:08:42.188 --> 00:08:46.159 align:middle line:84%
So how fast the neurons
are firing at any one time,

00:08:46.159 --> 00:08:47.994 align:middle line:84%
and that's represented
by different colors,

00:08:47.994 --> 00:08:49.062 align:middle line:90%
as we can see here.

00:08:49.062 --> 00:08:51.297 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:08:52.198 --> 00:08:54.768 align:middle line:84%
>> Scientists have discovered
that we cycle through four

00:08:54.768 --> 00:08:58.304 align:middle line:84%
distinct stages of sleep
approximately every 90 minutes.

00:09:04.077 --> 00:09:06.679 align:middle line:90%
Each has its own EEG signature.

00:09:06.679 --> 00:09:09.482 align:middle line:84%
And they reveal that, in
early stage one sleep,

00:09:09.482 --> 00:09:13.153 align:middle line:90%
the brain is still very active.

00:09:13.153 --> 00:09:15.922 align:middle line:84%
>> Certain areas of the brain
actually go off to sleep before

00:09:15.922 --> 00:09:16.990 align:middle line:90%
other parts.

00:09:16.990 --> 00:09:19.392 align:middle line:84%
We now know from very
challenging studies

00:09:19.392 --> 00:09:20.860 align:middle line:84%
with deep in-dwelling
electrodes,

00:09:20.860 --> 00:09:22.462 align:middle line:84%
right in the middle
of the brain,

00:09:22.462 --> 00:09:24.798 align:middle line:84%
that areas such as
the thalamus actually

00:09:24.798 --> 00:09:27.333 align:middle line:84%
go to sleep minutes before
the rest of the brain.

00:09:27.333 --> 00:09:30.670 align:middle line:84%
And can perhaps explain
those half-awake, half-asleep

00:09:30.670 --> 00:09:31.538 align:middle line:90%
feelings.

00:09:31.538 --> 00:09:33.440 align:middle line:10%
It's actually because
some area of the brain

00:09:33.440 --> 00:09:35.575 align:middle line:10%
are, in fact, asleep
while others are awake.

00:09:35.575 --> 00:09:37.343 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:09:38.144 --> 00:09:41.648 align:middle line:84%
>> Then, as the sleep cycle
progresses to stage two,

00:09:41.648 --> 00:09:46.753 align:middle line:84%
our heart rate slows down and
our body temperature drops.

00:09:46.753 --> 00:09:49.088 align:middle line:84%
>> This is the predominant
phase of sleep.

00:09:49.088 --> 00:09:54.194 align:middle line:84%
60% of the night, we
spent in stage two sleep.

00:09:54.194 --> 00:09:58.264 align:middle line:84%
>> Then we enter deep sleep when
our neurons pulse synchronously

00:09:58.264 --> 00:10:01.568 align:middle line:90%
in large, slow waves.

00:10:01.568 --> 00:10:03.970 align:middle line:84%
And for the first time
on Australian television,

00:10:03.970 --> 00:10:06.372 align:middle line:84%
we can hear the brain
during deep sleep.

00:10:06.372 --> 00:10:08.608 align:middle line:90%
[LOW VIBRATION]

00:10:13.847 --> 00:10:16.149 align:middle line:84%
Scientists from the
University of Sydney

00:10:16.149 --> 00:10:19.018 align:middle line:84%
created this sleep soundscape
especially for Catalyst.

00:10:22.121 --> 00:10:25.692 align:middle line:84%
The music reveals that even
during this relatively quiet

00:10:25.692 --> 00:10:28.027 align:middle line:84%
phase of sleep, the
brain is a long way

00:10:28.027 --> 00:10:30.563 align:middle line:90%
from being switched off.

00:10:30.563 --> 00:10:33.266 align:middle line:84%
>> You can hear the neurons
are firing together.

00:10:33.266 --> 00:10:35.268 align:middle line:84%
These really slow
right down, and you

00:10:35.268 --> 00:10:37.704 align:middle line:84%
get waves of synchronized,
slow activity moving

00:10:37.704 --> 00:10:38.571 align:middle line:90%
across the brain.

00:10:38.571 --> 00:10:40.974 align:middle line:90%
[LOW VIBRATION]

00:10:43.843 --> 00:10:45.912 align:middle line:84%
Perhaps the most familiar
stage of sleep to us

00:10:45.912 --> 00:10:50.717 align:middle line:90%
all is REM, when we dream.

00:10:50.717 --> 00:10:53.586 align:middle line:84%
It's during this phase that the
sleeping brain is at its most

00:10:53.586 --> 00:10:54.988 align:middle line:90%
active.

00:10:54.988 --> 00:10:56.322 align:middle line:90%
>> Things really go haywire.

00:10:56.322 --> 00:11:00.093 align:middle line:84%
Breathing gets much faster, so
your breathing rate speeds up.

00:11:00.093 --> 00:11:01.794 align:middle line:90%
Your heart rate speeds up.

00:11:01.794 --> 00:11:04.464 align:middle line:84%
There's a of dream
content going on.

00:11:04.464 --> 00:11:06.533 align:middle line:84%
And if you look at
the brain activity,

00:11:06.533 --> 00:11:11.437 align:middle line:84%
we really can't tell whether
you're awake or asleep.

00:11:11.437 --> 00:11:13.973 align:middle line:84%
>> It's easy to think that your
brain is completely shut down

00:11:13.973 --> 00:11:15.842 align:middle line:90%
while you're asleep.

00:11:15.842 --> 00:11:17.644 align:middle line:84%
But the ability to
detect and interpret

00:11:17.644 --> 00:11:19.812 align:middle line:84%
electrical signals
produced by the brain

00:11:19.812 --> 00:11:22.582 align:middle line:84%
to effectively look inside
is revealing that it couldn't

00:11:22.582 --> 00:11:24.350 align:middle line:90%
be further from the truth.

00:11:24.350 --> 00:11:26.019 align:middle line:90%
>> Time to wake up there, Reg.

00:11:26.019 --> 00:11:26.853 align:middle line:90%
How did you go?

00:11:26.853 --> 00:11:27.654 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah.

00:11:27.654 --> 00:11:31.124 align:middle line:90%
I was dreaming.

00:11:31.124 --> 00:11:33.593 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:11:38.064 --> 00:11:40.600 align:middle line:84%
>> Exactly what happens
while we sleep is still a bit

00:11:40.600 --> 00:11:42.769 align:middle line:90%
of a mystery.

00:11:42.769 --> 00:11:44.304 align:middle line:84%
But scientists do
understand some

00:11:44.304 --> 00:11:47.140 align:middle line:84%
of sleep's critical
functions, and that we need it

00:11:47.140 --> 00:11:50.610 align:middle line:84%
for optimal health
and well-being.

00:11:50.610 --> 00:11:51.578 align:middle line:90%
So sleep is important--

00:11:51.578 --> 00:11:52.378 align:middle line:90%
[ALARM RINGS]

00:11:52.378 --> 00:11:55.982 align:middle line:84%
--and we all worry about
not getting enough of it.

00:11:55.982 --> 00:11:58.885 align:middle line:84%
How do you know if your
body needs more time in bed?

00:11:58.885 --> 00:12:00.286 align:middle line:90%
[BABY FUSSING]

00:12:00.286 --> 00:12:01.788 align:middle line:90%
Here's a way to find out.

00:12:01.788 --> 00:12:03.122 align:middle line:90%
[BABY CRIES]

00:12:03.122 --> 00:12:03.990 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:12:03.990 --> 00:12:04.791 align:middle line:90%
[CHUCKLES]

00:12:04.791 --> 00:12:06.025 align:middle line:90%
>> It's [INAUDIBLE].

00:12:06.025 --> 00:12:07.760 align:middle line:90%
>> Meet Brooke.

00:12:07.760 --> 00:12:11.431 align:middle line:84%
Like myself, she and her
partner Chris are proud parents.

00:12:11.431 --> 00:12:14.968 align:middle line:84%
Beside with their new housemate,
five-month-old Olivia.

00:12:14.968 --> 00:12:16.302 align:middle line:90%
[CHUCKLES]

00:12:16.302 --> 00:12:17.770 align:middle line:84%
And of course, as
all new parents

00:12:17.770 --> 00:12:23.142 align:middle line:84%
know the hot topic is,
how much we miss sleep.

00:12:23.142 --> 00:12:25.645 align:middle line:90%
>> Never been as tired as this.

00:12:25.645 --> 00:12:28.247 align:middle line:90%
I didn't know what tired was.

00:12:28.247 --> 00:12:31.184 align:middle line:84%
>> As can be expected, they're
up several times a night.

00:12:31.184 --> 00:12:36.356 align:middle line:84%
>> She's never slept through the
night, so spaces of four hours.

00:12:36.356 --> 00:12:38.825 align:middle line:10%
There are times when your
adrenaline doesn't kick in.

00:12:38.825 --> 00:12:41.995 align:middle line:10%
And it's so hard pulling
yourself out of bed.

00:12:41.995 --> 00:12:44.397 align:middle line:90%
[CHUCKLES]

00:12:44.397 --> 00:12:50.937 align:middle line:84%
Coping best as I can, so coffee,
call on help if I'm desperate.

00:12:50.937 --> 00:12:53.806 align:middle line:84%
Luckily, I've got
a mum close by.

00:12:53.806 --> 00:12:55.642 align:middle line:84%
I've had a nap a
couple of times.

00:12:55.642 --> 00:12:59.278 align:middle line:84%
But that's actually
quite hard sometimes.

00:12:59.278 --> 00:13:02.382 align:middle line:84%
Just getting through the day,
waiting for that night period

00:13:02.382 --> 00:13:04.984 align:middle line:84%
to hit where we can
all go to bed again.

00:13:04.984 --> 00:13:05.952 align:middle line:90%
[CHUCKLES]

00:13:05.952 --> 00:13:07.120 align:middle line:90%
Do it all again.

00:13:07.120 --> 00:13:09.355 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:13:09.355 --> 00:13:13.626 align:middle line:84%
I notice myself, I'm changing
in a social situation.

00:13:13.626 --> 00:13:16.462 align:middle line:84%
There have been times where
I've replied in my mind

00:13:16.462 --> 00:13:19.999 align:middle line:90%
but I have not spoken.

00:13:19.999 --> 00:13:22.602 align:middle line:84%
Almost too tired to
have a conversation.

00:13:22.602 --> 00:13:28.541 align:middle line:84%
So I wonder if there's going to
be long term effects of that.

00:13:28.541 --> 00:13:32.211 align:middle line:84%
>> Tiredness, sleep
deprivation, fatigue, torture,

00:13:32.211 --> 00:13:35.748 align:middle line:84%
whatever we call it,
we've all felt it.

00:13:35.748 --> 00:13:38.418 align:middle line:10%
>> 4 out of 10 Australians
are getting inadequate sleep.

00:13:38.418 --> 00:13:40.553 align:middle line:10%
We know this from
a large report that

00:13:40.553 --> 00:13:43.923 align:middle line:10%
was just released from the
Sleep Health Foundation.

00:13:43.923 --> 00:13:45.958 align:middle line:84%
So these are really
quite alarming numbers.

00:13:45.958 --> 00:13:48.795 align:middle line:84%
And inadequate sleep is costing
the Australian community

00:13:48.795 --> 00:13:51.164 align:middle line:90%
$66 billion a year.

00:13:51.164 --> 00:13:53.199 align:middle line:84%
So it really is a big
problem in our society.

00:13:53.199 --> 00:13:55.568 align:middle line:84%
And one of the three
pillars of health, getting

00:13:55.568 --> 00:13:57.637 align:middle line:90%
enough and good quality sleep.

00:13:57.637 --> 00:13:59.872 align:middle line:90%
Many of us are not.

00:13:59.872 --> 00:14:00.840 align:middle line:90%
[BEEP]

00:14:03.743 --> 00:14:06.145 align:middle line:90%
[DOOR CLOSES]

00:14:06.145 --> 00:14:09.215 align:middle line:84%
>> One of the ways scientists
can measure tiredness is to use

00:14:09.215 --> 00:14:13.086 align:middle line:84%
the sleep onset latency test,
where they repeatedly measure

00:14:13.086 --> 00:14:18.191 align:middle line:84%
the length of time taken to fall
asleep during a daytime nap.

00:14:18.191 --> 00:14:20.293 align:middle line:84%
To find out how
tired she is, Brooke

00:14:20.293 --> 00:14:23.496 align:middle line:84%
is going to do just that,
time herself as she nods off.

00:14:26.833 --> 00:14:29.502 align:middle line:84%
It's important that
conditions are just right.

00:14:29.502 --> 00:14:34.240 align:middle line:84%
She's in a quiet, cool
room with curtains drawn.

00:14:34.240 --> 00:14:37.176 align:middle line:84%
In the room, there is
a metal tray and spoon.

00:14:37.176 --> 00:14:39.112 align:middle line:84%
Brooke has to hold
the spoon in her hand

00:14:39.112 --> 00:14:41.681 align:middle line:84%
so it rests just over
the edge of the bed

00:14:41.681 --> 00:14:43.116 align:middle line:90%
directly above the tray.

00:14:45.985 --> 00:14:48.221 align:middle line:84%
If the test is
successful, the spoon

00:14:48.221 --> 00:14:51.657 align:middle line:84%
will fall from her hand once
she falls asleep [CLANG]

00:14:51.657 --> 00:14:54.460 align:middle line:84%
and hit the metal
tray, waking her up.

00:14:54.460 --> 00:14:55.928 align:middle line:90%
[TICKING]

00:15:11.544 --> 00:15:12.545 align:middle line:90%
[CLANG]

00:15:12.545 --> 00:15:15.148 align:middle line:84%
As soon as she's woken by
the sound of the spoon,

00:15:15.148 --> 00:15:17.950 align:middle line:84%
she needs to stop the
stopwatch and see how long it

00:15:17.950 --> 00:15:19.118 align:middle line:90%
took her to drift off.

00:15:21.921 --> 00:15:24.891 align:middle line:84%
>> If you're falling asleep
in less than five minutes,

00:15:24.891 --> 00:15:27.693 align:middle line:84%
that's a sign that your
profoundly sleep deprived

00:15:27.693 --> 00:15:30.530 align:middle line:84%
or you may have one of
these sleep disorders.

00:15:30.530 --> 00:15:35.001 align:middle line:84%
If you're not falling asleep at
all in these 20 minute cycles

00:15:35.001 --> 00:15:38.137 align:middle line:84%
or you're falling asleep
in 15 minutes or more,

00:15:38.137 --> 00:15:41.707 align:middle line:84%
it's a sign that things are
quite normal and you're alert.

00:15:41.707 --> 00:15:44.043 align:middle line:84%
>> So there you have it, if
you're dropping off to sleep

00:15:44.043 --> 00:15:46.012 align:middle line:84%
in under five minutes
during the day,

00:15:46.012 --> 00:15:48.381 align:middle line:84%
then you're probably
sleep deprived.

00:15:48.381 --> 00:15:50.483 align:middle line:84%
>> I could've
snoozed for longer.

00:15:50.483 --> 00:15:51.284 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:15:51.284 --> 00:15:52.185 align:middle line:90%
>> I'm sorry to wake you.

00:15:52.185 --> 00:15:52.985 align:middle line:90%
>> No.

00:15:52.985 --> 00:15:54.187 align:middle line:90%
[CHUCKLES]

00:15:54.187 --> 00:15:56.055 align:middle line:84%
>> A quick spoon test
shows that mom, Brooke,

00:15:56.055 --> 00:15:58.758 align:middle line:84%
seems to be balancing the
demands of parenthood far

00:15:58.758 --> 00:16:00.393 align:middle line:90%
better than she thought.

00:16:00.393 --> 00:16:01.360 align:middle line:90%
>> What is that?

00:16:01.360 --> 00:16:04.297 align:middle line:90%
22 minutes.

00:16:04.297 --> 00:16:07.500 align:middle line:90%
[CHUCKLES]

00:16:07.500 --> 00:16:08.701 align:middle line:90%
I believe it.

00:16:08.701 --> 00:16:12.238 align:middle line:84%
But I'm shocked that
I'm not sleep deprived.

00:16:12.238 --> 00:16:13.206 align:middle line:90%
Well, that's good news.

00:16:20.313 --> 00:16:22.148 align:middle line:84%
>> So if you're
tired, go to bed.

00:16:22.148 --> 00:16:23.983 align:middle line:10%
Seems obvious, right?

00:16:23.983 --> 00:16:26.886 align:middle line:10%
And actually, Aussies are
pretty good at doing just that.

00:16:26.886 --> 00:16:28.855 align:middle line:84%
A recent study found
that on average we

00:16:28.855 --> 00:16:31.757 align:middle line:84%
go to bed earlier than almost
any other country in the world,

00:16:31.757 --> 00:16:33.993 align:middle line:90%
at 10:45 in the evening.

00:16:33.993 --> 00:16:37.296 align:middle line:84%
But of course, there are some
of us who aren't average.

00:16:37.296 --> 00:16:39.632 align:middle line:10%
>> I'm definitely a night owl.

00:16:39.632 --> 00:16:42.969 align:middle line:84%
Each morning when I get up in
the morning, it's a struggle.

00:16:42.969 --> 00:16:44.637 align:middle line:84%
Getting up in the
morning is a struggle.

00:16:44.637 --> 00:16:48.241 align:middle line:84%
Staying late at night is never
a struggle for me, usually.

00:16:48.241 --> 00:16:49.976 align:middle line:84%
>> The way people
describe being--

00:16:49.976 --> 00:16:52.378 align:middle line:84%
not being morning people, I
feel that way at night, being

00:16:52.378 --> 00:16:53.512 align:middle line:90%
really irritated and stuff.

00:16:53.512 --> 00:16:55.815 align:middle line:84%
If I can't go to sleep
when I'm sleepy at night,

00:16:55.815 --> 00:17:00.119 align:middle line:84%
I just get really angry
and irrationally pissed off

00:17:00.119 --> 00:17:01.487 align:middle line:90%
at people.

00:17:01.487 --> 00:17:06.192 align:middle line:84%
>> Usually, when I stay up
late it's because I've been out

00:17:06.192 --> 00:17:10.663 align:middle line:84%
partying with friends, which
involves a bit of drinking,

00:17:10.663 --> 00:17:13.465 align:middle line:84%
obviously, and
chatting, and laughing,

00:17:13.465 --> 00:17:14.433 align:middle line:90%
and that kind of stuff.

00:17:14.433 --> 00:17:17.169 align:middle line:84%
And so that's what
happens usually.

00:17:17.169 --> 00:17:21.140 align:middle line:84%
>> I have to stay up to at
least 11:00, sometimes midnight.

00:17:21.140 --> 00:17:26.012 align:middle line:84%
And then even so, then I'll
read sometimes for up to an hour

00:17:26.012 --> 00:17:28.281 align:middle line:90%
until I think I can go to sleep.

00:17:28.281 --> 00:17:30.883 align:middle line:84%
Because I know there's
no point in going to bed

00:17:30.883 --> 00:17:32.518 align:middle line:84%
and trying to force
myself to sleep.

00:17:32.518 --> 00:17:34.954 align:middle line:84%
>> What I liked about you was
you're a night person and you

00:17:34.954 --> 00:17:36.255 align:middle line:90%
always seem to be jolly.

00:17:36.255 --> 00:17:39.325 align:middle line:84%
And you could always sort
of keep going at a party--

00:17:39.325 --> 00:17:40.126 align:middle line:90%
>> Hmm.

00:17:40.126 --> 00:17:41.694 align:middle line:90%
>> --late into the night.

00:17:41.694 --> 00:17:43.663 align:middle line:90%
>> Yes, well I am a night owl.

00:17:43.663 --> 00:17:44.463 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah, so am I.

00:17:44.463 --> 00:17:47.199 align:middle line:84%
>> But-- and then annoyingly,
I'm a morning person as well.

00:17:47.199 --> 00:17:49.702 align:middle line:84%
And sometimes I get in
trouble for being too bouncy

00:17:49.702 --> 00:17:50.503 align:middle line:90%
in the morning.

00:17:50.503 --> 00:17:54.240 align:middle line:84%
So all of this leads to
basically not enough sleep.

00:17:54.240 --> 00:17:56.342 align:middle line:84%
>> There's usually
partying, yes.

00:18:00.012 --> 00:18:03.082 align:middle line:84%
>> But whether you're a party
animal or an early bird,

00:18:03.082 --> 00:18:05.117 align:middle line:84%
we now know it's not
just a preference.

00:18:05.117 --> 00:18:08.487 align:middle line:90%
>> Ow.

00:18:08.487 --> 00:18:11.490 align:middle line:84%
>> Apparently, [CHIRPS]
early to bed, early to rise,

00:18:11.490 --> 00:18:14.727 align:middle line:84%
makes a man healthy,
wealthy, and wise.

00:18:14.727 --> 00:18:16.495 align:middle line:90%
[DING]

00:18:16.495 --> 00:18:18.798 align:middle line:84%
But what if you're
a night owl like me?

00:18:18.798 --> 00:18:20.900 align:middle line:84%
[OWL HOOT] No matter
what we do, we simply

00:18:20.900 --> 00:18:24.103 align:middle line:84%
can't fall asleep
until the wee hours.

00:18:24.103 --> 00:18:26.238 align:middle line:84%
Well, the very latest
research suggests

00:18:26.238 --> 00:18:29.308 align:middle line:84%
our late to bed tendencies
could be hardwired in our genes.

00:18:29.308 --> 00:18:32.311 align:middle line:84%
[OWL HOOT] In fact, science now
recognizes [CHIRPS] the morning

00:18:32.311 --> 00:18:34.780 align:middle line:84%
lark, and its opposite
the night owl,

00:18:34.780 --> 00:18:36.716 align:middle line:90%
are two distinct chronotypes.

00:18:36.716 --> 00:18:40.519 align:middle line:10%
[OWL HOOT]

00:18:40.519 --> 00:18:44.056 align:middle line:10%
Owls outperform larks on
most intelligence measures.

00:18:44.056 --> 00:18:47.226 align:middle line:84%
[CHIRPS] And evening
types are not just brainy,

00:18:47.226 --> 00:18:49.996 align:middle line:84%
they've also been shown
to be prolific lovers.

00:18:49.996 --> 00:18:52.798 align:middle line:84%
[OWL HOOT] Owls are
partial to bad habits

00:18:52.798 --> 00:18:55.968 align:middle line:84%
like smoking and
drinking, consistent

00:18:55.968 --> 00:18:59.005 align:middle line:84%
with a broad personality trait
that researchers call novelty

00:18:59.005 --> 00:18:59.805 align:middle line:90%
seeking.

00:19:02.575 --> 00:19:04.410 align:middle line:90%
[WHISTLE]

00:19:04.410 --> 00:19:07.213 align:middle line:84%
Larks on the other hand,
are much more co-operative,

00:19:07.213 --> 00:19:09.949 align:middle line:84%
agreeable, and
conscientious than owls.

00:19:09.949 --> 00:19:11.617 align:middle line:90%
[GRUNT]

00:19:11.617 --> 00:19:13.986 align:middle line:84%
Sounds a bit goody two
shoes to an owl like me.

00:19:13.986 --> 00:19:14.787 align:middle line:90%
[COOS]

00:19:14.787 --> 00:19:17.423 align:middle line:10%
So am I doomed to pad
around my dark house

00:19:17.423 --> 00:19:21.761 align:middle line:10%
until the early
hours every night

00:19:21.761 --> 00:19:24.230 align:middle line:10%
or can I reprogram
my internal clock

00:19:24.230 --> 00:19:26.832 align:middle line:10%
to fit better with a
modern 9 to 5 life?

00:19:26.832 --> 00:19:27.633 align:middle line:90%
[TICKING]

00:19:27.633 --> 00:19:30.102 align:middle line:84%
Surprisingly, it's
something we all already do.

00:19:30.102 --> 00:19:30.903 align:middle line:90%
[CUCKOO]

00:19:30.903 --> 00:19:34.840 align:middle line:84%
The average body clock runs at
around 24 hours and 11 minutes.

00:19:34.840 --> 00:19:37.777 align:middle line:84%
Yet, we live on a pretty
tight 24 hour cycle.

00:19:37.777 --> 00:19:40.379 align:middle line:84%
And that means, most
of us reset our rhythm

00:19:40.379 --> 00:19:41.981 align:middle line:90%
by 11 minutes each day.

00:19:41.981 --> 00:19:43.249 align:middle line:90%
[GROANS]

00:19:43.249 --> 00:19:47.620 align:middle line:84%
So that could be why many
of us hit the snooze button.

00:19:47.620 --> 00:19:50.022 align:middle line:84%
We're just not ready to
wake up until 11 minutes

00:19:50.022 --> 00:19:52.324 align:middle line:90%
after our alarm goes off.

00:19:52.324 --> 00:19:53.225 align:middle line:90%
[CHIRPS]

00:19:53.225 --> 00:19:55.094 align:middle line:84%
Whether you're an
owl or a lark, you

00:19:55.094 --> 00:19:58.230 align:middle line:84%
still need your seven to eight
hour sleep to be at your best.

00:19:58.230 --> 00:19:59.031 align:middle line:90%
[COOS]

00:19:59.031 --> 00:19:59.832 align:middle line:90%
[ROOSTER CROWS]

00:19:59.832 --> 00:20:02.668 align:middle line:10%
That is, unless you are
a short sleeper, one

00:20:02.668 --> 00:20:04.336 align:middle line:10%
of only a few
people who naturally

00:20:04.336 --> 00:20:06.839 align:middle line:10%
sleep two or three hours
less than the rest of us

00:20:06.839 --> 00:20:09.375 align:middle line:10%
and still feels refreshed.

00:20:09.375 --> 00:20:12.745 align:middle line:90%
But I'm not one of those.

00:20:12.745 --> 00:20:14.213 align:middle line:90%
[SINGE]

00:20:14.213 --> 00:20:15.648 align:middle line:90%
[STATIC]

00:20:15.648 --> 00:20:19.518 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:20:19.518 --> 00:20:22.521 align:middle line:84%
But whether you're an
owl or a lark, some of us

00:20:22.521 --> 00:20:26.492 align:middle line:84%
don't have a choice
about when we go to bed.

00:20:26.492 --> 00:20:30.663 align:middle line:84%
Over 200,000 people in
Australia regularly work nights.

00:20:30.663 --> 00:20:33.632 align:middle line:84%
>> Do you mind if I asked you
some questions about sleep?

00:20:33.632 --> 00:20:35.034 align:middle line:84%
>> Sleep is a waste
of time, mate.

00:20:35.034 --> 00:20:37.002 align:middle line:84%
>> Then how much sleep
are you getting a night?

00:20:37.002 --> 00:20:37.970 align:middle line:90%
>> Three or four hours.

00:20:37.970 --> 00:20:38.938 align:middle line:90%
>> Three or four hours?

00:20:38.938 --> 00:20:39.772 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah.

00:20:39.772 --> 00:20:41.373 align:middle line:90%
>> For how long?

00:20:41.373 --> 00:20:42.408 align:middle line:90%
>> 56 years.

00:20:42.408 --> 00:20:44.710 align:middle line:84%
>> So that's not many
hours sleep though.

00:20:44.710 --> 00:20:44.844 align:middle line:90%
>> Three hours.

00:20:44.844 --> 00:20:45.978 align:middle line:90%
>> That's like three hours.

00:20:45.978 --> 00:20:48.347 align:middle line:84%
>> Do a lot of work
in three hours.

00:20:48.347 --> 00:20:50.983 align:middle line:84%
>> Science is now revealing that
working when you really should

00:20:50.983 --> 00:20:54.520 align:middle line:84%
be sleeping is not
very good for you.

00:20:54.520 --> 00:20:55.955 align:middle line:90%
[CHATTER]

00:21:00.693 --> 00:21:03.562 align:middle line:84%
Just like me, Triple
J DJ, Hau Latukefu

00:21:03.562 --> 00:21:05.164 align:middle line:90%
works irregular night shifts.

00:21:07.933 --> 00:21:10.302 align:middle line:84%
Once a week, he heads off
to work while most of us

00:21:10.302 --> 00:21:13.506 align:middle line:84%
are just winding down
after a long day.

00:21:13.506 --> 00:21:15.307 align:middle line:90%
>> It's a lovely ride in.

00:21:15.307 --> 00:21:16.775 align:middle line:84%
Usually I'll play
music everywhere.

00:21:16.775 --> 00:21:18.110 align:middle line:10%
Whatever I do, music always.

00:21:18.110 --> 00:21:21.547 align:middle line:10%
But to and from work,
I don't play music.

00:21:21.547 --> 00:21:23.582 align:middle line:84%
I'm just that,
silence as well as

00:21:23.582 --> 00:21:26.619 align:middle line:84%
is quite-- there's something
beautiful in that silence

00:21:26.619 --> 00:21:29.155 align:middle line:84%
and driving through the city,
and the lights, and the people,

00:21:29.155 --> 00:21:31.957 align:middle line:90%
and the hustle and bustle.

00:21:31.957 --> 00:21:36.061 align:middle line:84%
>> To work late, Hau has to
override his urge to sleep

00:21:36.061 --> 00:21:39.031 align:middle line:84%
because scientists now know we
all have an internal clock that

00:21:39.031 --> 00:21:41.867 align:middle line:84%
makes us feel
tired at nighttime.

00:21:41.867 --> 00:21:44.803 align:middle line:84%
>> We have evolved specifically
to be diurnal animals,

00:21:44.803 --> 00:21:46.839 align:middle line:84%
so it mainly means
we're day active.

00:21:46.839 --> 00:21:49.074 align:middle line:10%
One of the things that
propels this cycle

00:21:49.074 --> 00:21:50.910 align:middle line:10%
is the existence of
the sleep pressure,

00:21:50.910 --> 00:21:53.078 align:middle line:10%
meaning the longer we're
awake, the more pressure we

00:21:53.078 --> 00:21:54.180 align:middle line:10%
have to sleep.

00:21:54.180 --> 00:21:56.649 align:middle line:84%
The basis for that is there
are sudden chemicals that

00:21:56.649 --> 00:21:59.818 align:middle line:84%
build up in the brain
that promote sleep.

00:21:59.818 --> 00:22:02.388 align:middle line:10%
>> But despite the buildup of
sleep pressure towards the end

00:22:02.388 --> 00:22:05.324 align:middle line:10%
of the day, we're all pretty
good at pushing the boundaries

00:22:05.324 --> 00:22:10.462 align:middle line:10%
of our internal body
clocks, whether it's coffee,

00:22:10.462 --> 00:22:14.767 align:middle line:10%
energy drinks, or good old
adrenaline that keeps us going.

00:22:14.767 --> 00:22:20.573 align:middle line:84%
>> Get in, 7:00/7:30, prep, on
air from 10:00, finish at 1:00.

00:22:20.573 --> 00:22:23.842 align:middle line:84%
And usually, the adrenaline
is still pumping.

00:22:23.842 --> 00:22:28.147 align:middle line:10%
So I'll leave here
within an hour

00:22:28.147 --> 00:22:30.282 align:middle line:10%
and then kind of drive home.

00:22:30.282 --> 00:22:33.552 align:middle line:10%
And even still I'm just
kind of winding down.

00:22:33.552 --> 00:22:37.957 align:middle line:10%
So I might be sleep
2:30/3:00, sometimes 3:30.

00:22:37.957 --> 00:22:38.757 align:middle line:90%
Yes, indeed.

00:22:38.757 --> 00:22:40.492 align:middle line:84%
Thursday evening,
week in week out.

00:22:40.492 --> 00:22:41.527 align:middle line:90%
You know what time it is.

00:22:41.527 --> 00:22:43.462 align:middle line:84%
It's the time for the
Triple J hip-hop show.

00:22:43.462 --> 00:22:45.864 align:middle line:84%
We're going to kick it off
with the sounds of AB Original.

00:22:45.864 --> 00:22:48.834 align:middle line:84%
Maurice send that up proper,
dance song in the house.

00:22:48.834 --> 00:22:49.702 align:middle line:90%
Yes, sir.

00:22:49.702 --> 00:22:50.903 align:middle line:90%
Make sure you keep it locked.

00:22:50.903 --> 00:22:54.206 align:middle line:84%
>> But not getting enough sleep
regularly and at the right time

00:22:54.206 --> 00:22:56.308 align:middle line:90%
does have its side effects.

00:22:56.308 --> 00:22:58.611 align:middle line:84%
>> To actually adapt to
those type of schedules,

00:22:58.611 --> 00:23:00.946 align:middle line:84%
it's important to live on
them very consistently.

00:23:00.946 --> 00:23:03.082 align:middle line:84%
A circadian clock
is only so flexible.

00:23:03.082 --> 00:23:05.784 align:middle line:84%
It can change timezones,
for example, when we travel.

00:23:05.784 --> 00:23:08.120 align:middle line:84%
It takes several days to
move to a new time zone.

00:23:08.120 --> 00:23:10.089 align:middle line:84%
The same problem is
experienced when we rapidly

00:23:10.089 --> 00:23:13.692 align:middle line:84%
change our sleep rate patterns
between days of the week.

00:23:13.692 --> 00:23:16.729 align:middle line:84%
So for example, someone who
irregularly works night shifts

00:23:16.729 --> 00:23:21.033 align:middle line:84%
is going to have a lot of
trouble adapting to that.

00:23:21.033 --> 00:23:24.637 align:middle line:84%
>> So Hau effectively suffers
a kind of social jet lag every

00:23:24.637 --> 00:23:25.771 align:middle line:90%
Friday.

00:23:25.771 --> 00:23:28.207 align:middle line:84%
>> Friday morning is not too
bad because I just get up.

00:23:28.207 --> 00:23:30.376 align:middle line:84%
And it's like, OK,
I got things to do.

00:23:30.376 --> 00:23:35.114 align:middle line:84%
And usually around
6:00, 7:00, 8:00,

00:23:35.114 --> 00:23:37.416 align:middle line:84%
I kind of feel like
I'm fading a bit.

00:23:40.886 --> 00:23:42.955 align:middle line:84%
I notice that I feel
tired if I sit still.

00:23:42.955 --> 00:23:45.524 align:middle line:84%
If I watch TV or
if I read a book,

00:23:45.524 --> 00:23:50.429 align:middle line:84%
then I can feel myself
kind of drifting off.

00:23:50.429 --> 00:23:53.766 align:middle line:90%
That's why I'm always moving.

00:23:53.766 --> 00:23:56.302 align:middle line:84%
>> Aside from feeling a
bit fuzzy on a Friday,

00:23:56.302 --> 00:23:59.305 align:middle line:84%
Hau's night shift doesn't really
affect him if he catches up

00:23:59.305 --> 00:24:01.640 align:middle line:90%
on sleep during the week.

00:24:01.640 --> 00:24:04.643 align:middle line:84%
But scientists now know that
shift workers who constantly

00:24:04.643 --> 00:24:07.813 align:middle line:84%
change their sleep wake cycles
can suffer dramatic health

00:24:07.813 --> 00:24:09.715 align:middle line:90%
consequences.

00:24:09.715 --> 00:24:12.518 align:middle line:84%
>> There are many
epidemiological studies showing

00:24:12.518 --> 00:24:15.220 align:middle line:84%
that living against the
clock is bad for you,

00:24:15.220 --> 00:24:16.855 align:middle line:84%
in terms of
cardiovascular outcomes,

00:24:16.855 --> 00:24:19.591 align:middle line:84%
in terms of cancer outcomes,
and in terms of diabetes,

00:24:19.591 --> 00:24:22.761 align:middle line:90%
and other metabolic outcomes.

00:24:22.761 --> 00:24:24.997 align:middle line:84%
We also know that you
get worse quality sleep

00:24:24.997 --> 00:24:27.633 align:middle line:84%
if you're attempting to sleep at
times that the circadian clock

00:24:27.633 --> 00:24:28.767 align:middle line:90%
is not permissive of sleep.

00:24:28.767 --> 00:24:30.703 align:middle line:84%
>> I think you
need a bigger cup.

